properties.Title: Blizzard Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:

properties.Title: Update: High Water Advisory Alert For Portions Of The Red River
properties.Summary:
Description: Update: This is a Manitoba Emergency Alert. Manitoba Infrastructure's Hydrologic Forecast Centre has issued a High Water Advisory for the Red River from St. Jean Baptiste through the City of Winnipeg (except for Ste. Agathe) due to expected high flows. If you are in the affected area, be watchful of local waterways as flooding is likely to occur. Do not attempt to cross fast flowing waters or waters of unknown depth. Avoid flooded areas. Follow all directions by the local authorities. Listen for updates and take all necessary precautions to stay safe. Up-to-date information is available at www.gov.mb.ca/flooding and www.manitoba511.ca or stay tuned to local media.

properties.Summary:

properties.Summary:

Total snowfall amounts of 15 to 25 cm can be expected in or around Qikiqtarjuaq. properties.Title: Snow Squall Watch In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Snow squalls possible today. Snow squalls are expected to continue off Lake Nipigon today behind a strong cold front. There is a possibility that the squalls will continue through Monday as winds are expected to remain out of the north or northwest. Localized accumulations of 10 to 15 cm are possible by this evening with additional snowfall possible on Monday. Travel conditions along Highway 11 could be particularly hazardous. Motorists are advised to watch for quickly changing weather conditions and adjust their driving accordingly. ### Travel may be hazardous due to sudden changes in the weather. Visibility may be suddenly reduced at times in heavy snow. Road closures are possible. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to ONstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #ONStorm.

properties.Title: Special Weather Statement In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: A snowfall to start the week. A low pressure system over the Northeastern United States will bring snow over Southern Quebec late in the afternoon on Monday. The snow will intensify in the evening and persist during the day on Tuesday, reaching Eastern Quebec. The morning commute will be particularly difficult Tuesday morning. 10 to 15 centimetres of snow is expected over Southern and Central Quebec and possibly more in the Eastern Townships, the Beauce and Eastern Quebec. The snow will be accompanied by strong winds over Central and Eastern Quebec, reducing visibilities in blowing snow. Accumulating snow will make travel difficult. Hazardous driving conditions can be expected due to reduced visibilities. The public is advised to monitor future forecasts for more information as the low pressure system's track becomes more certain. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to QCstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #QCStorm.
Expires: 2019-11-11T01:45:33-00:00

Description: Approaching storm to bring significant rainfall Tuesday into Wednesday morning. A developing system will affect Nova Scotia beginning late Monday night or early Tuesday. While it is too soon to provide specific details, the potential exists for a brief period of snow Monday night followed by significant amounts of rain and strong winds beginning Tuesday morning. Additional information will be provided as the details become more certain. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NSstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NSStorm.
